==English==

===Etymology===
* First attested in 1541.
* From {{etyl|la|en}} {{term/t|la|abdicātus||renounced}}, perfect passive participle of {{term/t|la|abdicō||renounce, reject, disclaim}}, formed from {{term|ab||away|lang=la}} + {{term/t|la|dicō||proclaim, dedicate, declare}}, akin to {{term/t|la|dīcō||say}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/ˈæb.dɪˌkeɪt/}}
* {{a|US}}
* {{audio|En-us-abdicate.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|abdicat|ing}}

# {{context|transitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To [[disclaim]] and [[expel]] from the family, as a father his child; to [[disown]]; to [[disinherit]]. {{defdate|Attested from the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century until the early 19<sup>th</sup> century.}}
# {{context|transitive|reflexive|obsolete|lang=en}} To formally separate oneself from or to divest oneself of. {{defdate|First attested from the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century until the late 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}
# {{context|transitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To [[depose]]. {{defdate|Attested from the early 17<sup>th</sup> century until the late 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}
# {{context|transitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To [[reject]]; to [[cast off]]; to discard. {{defdate|Attested from the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century until the late 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}
#: {{rfquotek|Bishop Hall}}
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[surrender]], [[renounce]] or [[relinquish]], as sovereign power; to [[withdraw]] [[definitely]] from filling or [[exercising]], as a high office, station, dignity; as, to ''abdicate'' the throne, the crown, the [[papacy]]; to fail to fulfill responsibility for. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}
#: ''Note:'' The word ''abdicate'' was held to mean, in the case of James II, to abandon without a formal surrender.
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:Edward Gibbon|Edward Gibbon]]:
#*: The cross-bearers '''abdicated''' their service.
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:Edmund Burke|Edmund Burke]]:
#*: He '''abdicates''' all right to be his own governor.
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:James Anthony Froude|James Anthony Froude]]:
#*: The understanding '''abdicates''' its functions.
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To relinquish or renounce a throne, or other high office or dignity; to renounce [[sovereignty]]. {{defdate|First attested in the early 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:Edmund Burke|Edmund Burke]]:
#*: Though a king may '''abdicate''' for his own person, he cannot '''abdicate''' for the monarchy.

